##
Build a new document type called “Residual Solvent Risk Assessment Report” as a fully isolated workflow from the existing Elemental Impurity Assessment workflow. Do not reuse EI-specific assumptions, EI element classes, EI Q3D PDE logic, EI 30% PDE rows, EI class-wise tables, EI parenteral/oral PDE routing, EI annexure schema, or EI generate_report.js table builders for this report type. Residual Solvent reports follow USP <467> and ICH Q3C logic, not ICH Q3D logic. The residual solvent workflow must be product-agnostic, low-touch, audit-traceable, validation-safe, and must not break or modify the existing EI OSD/injection workflows.

At the app.py level, add document type routing so the user first selects report type. When the user selects Elemental Impurity Assessment, keep the existing EI workflow exactly unchanged. When the user selects Residual Solvent Risk Assessment, route the request into a separate residual-solvent workflow branch with its own Excel parser, annexure converter/parser, annexure mapping logic, calculation engine, validation gate, payload builder, and separate A4 renderer. app.py should behave as an orchestrator only and must not mix EI and residual solvent logic in the same calculation functions. The residual solvent branch should accept product metadata, composition/calculation Excel, and residual solvent annexures if available. It must extract maximum daily dose / maximum daily intake / amount in maximum dose from the Excel whenever possible, show extracted values to the user for verification, allow edits only for missing or low-confidence values, then generate the report only after validation passes.

The Residual Solvent report structure must be fixed as a residual-solvent TSR format, not copied from EI. The report should follow this section order: title/header page, abstract, table of contents, 1.0 Objective, 2.0 Details of Product, 3.0 Background, 4.0 Drug Product Composition, 5.0 Residual Solvents Risk Assessment, 6.0 Conclusion, 7.0 Summary and Conclusion, 8.0 References, 9.0 List of Annexures, 10.0 Revision History, and Electronic Signatures. The renderer must use an A4-style residual solvent layout, not the current EI A5 landscape layout. The approved residual solvent example uses product header metadata, a product details table, a unit composition table, a supplier declaration table, nested residual solvent calculation tables, conclusion/summary sections, references, annexure list, revision history, and signatures. The new renderer must produce this report type as a residual solvent document, not as an EI report with renamed columns. The uploaded approved example confirms this residual solvent structure and nested solvent-table style. [1](https://drlglobal-my.sharepoint.com/personal/nitinreddyv_drreddys_com/_layouts/15/Doc.aspx?sourcedoc=%7B503FFB07-9F64-4F4F-93AA-512644B4254A%7D&file=Residual%20Solvent-%20Esomeprazole%20Mg%20DR%20OS%2009-02-2026%202.xlsx&action=default&mobileredirect=true)

Create a separate residual solvent Excel parser. The Excel parser must support both detailed and basic Excel formats. In detailed Excel mode, the Excel may already contain no. of doses, components, quantity/unit, amount in maximum dose, solvent names, nested limit/daily-exposure columns, total daily exposure rows, and residual solvent limits as per USP <467>. In the uploaded detailed Excel, Sheet 1 contains “No. of doses = 6”, component names, “Quantity / unit (mg)”, “Amount in Maximum Dose (mg)”, multiple solvents such as Ethanol, Ethylene Glycol, 1,4-Dioxane, Iso Propyl Alcohol, Tertiary butyl alcohol, Heptane, Acetone, Methanol, and Toluene, with each solvent having “Limit (ppm)” and “Daily Exposure (mg)” subcolumns. Sheet 2 contains cumulative composition by stages such as Seal Coating, Drug Layering, Sub Coating, Enteric Coating, Lubrication, Inactive Granules, and Total. The parser must extract all of this when present and preserve the Excel table for rendering and audit. [1](https://drlglobal-my.sharepoint.com/personal/nitinreddyv_drreddys_com/_layouts/15/Doc.aspx?sourcedoc=%7B503FFB07-9F64-4F4F-93AA-512644B4254A%7D&file=Residual%20Solvent-%20Esomeprazole%20Mg%20DR%20OS%2009-02-2026%202.xlsx&action=default&mobileredirect=true)

The Excel parser must not assume that every user will upload a fully calculated Excel. The parser must implement a daily-intake hierarchy and normalize all daily intake data internally to component_amount_in_maximum_dose_mg. Highest priority: if “Amount in Maximum Dose (mg)” exists, use it directly. Second priority: if “Maximum Daily Intake (g)” or “MDD (g)” exists, convert to mg/day. Third priority: if “MDD (mg)” or component-level daily amount in mg exists, use it directly. Fourth priority: if “Quantity / unit (mg)” and “No. of doses” exist, calculate Amount in Maximum Dose (mg) = Quantity/unit × No. of doses. Fifth priority: if only composition exists but no dose basis exists, ask the user for maximum dose basis before calculation. This must mirror the direct-MDD edge case solved for injection documents: if the user provides direct MDD or maximum daily intake, the report must still generate without requiring unnecessary ratio, dose-volume, or strength inputs.

The residual solvent calculation engine must be separate from the EI calculation engine. Residual solvent exposure is calculated as: Daily Exposure (mg/day) = Amount in Maximum Dose (mg/day) × Solvent Limit (ppm) / 1,000,000. For example, if Triethyl citrate has Amount in Maximum Dose = 23.46 mg and Ethanol limit = 5000 ppm, the calculated daily exposure is 23.46 × 5000 / 1,000,000 = 0.1173 mg/day, which matches the approved residual solvent report and Excel. [1](https://drlglobal-my.sharepoint.com/personal/nitinreddyv_drreddys_com/_layouts/15/Doc.aspx?sourcedoc=%7B503FFB07-9F64-4F4F-93AA-512644B4254A%7D&file=Residual%20Solvent-%20Esomeprazole%20Mg%20DR%20OS%2009-02-2026%202.xlsx&action=default&mobileredirect=true)[1](https://drlglobal-my.sharepoint.com/personal/nitinreddyv_drreddys_com/_layouts/15/Doc.aspx?sourcedoc=%7B503FFB07-9F64-4F4F-93AA-512644B4254A%7D&file=Residual%20Solvent-%20Esomeprazole%20Mg%20DR%20OS%2009-02-2026%202.xlsx&action=default&mobileredirect=true) Do not use EI formula units such as g/day × µg/g = µg/day in this workflow. Do not generate 30% PDE thresholds. Do not use EI element lists or Q3D elemental classes. Residual solvent comparison must use USP <467>/ICH Q3C solvent limits and PDE/Option logic, with exposure in mg/day and concentration limits in ppm.

Implement a residual solvent master-data layer separate from ICH_Q3D. This master must contain residual solvent names, common synonyms, class where relevant, USP <467>/ICH Q3C concentration limit in ppm, PDE/exposure limit in mg/day where relevant, and supported aliases such as IPA / Isopropyl Alcohol / Iso Propyl Alcohol, TBA / tert-Butyl alcohol / Tertiary butyl alcohol, Ethanol / Ethyl alcohol, etc. This must not be mixed into ICH_PDE. The report must compare total daily exposure per solvent against the residual solvent limit row. In the detailed Excel example, the bottom rows include total daily exposure values and “Residual solvent Limit as per current USP <467>” values, and those must be extracted and validated when present. [1](https://drlglobal-my.sharepoint.com/personal/nitinreddyv_drreddys_com/_layouts/15/Doc.aspx?sourcedoc=%7B503FFB07-9F64-4F4F-93AA-512644B4254A%7D&file=Residual%20Solvent-%20Esomeprazole%20Mg%20DR%20OS%2009-02-2026%202.xlsx&action=default&mobileredirect=true)

Create a separate residual_solvent_annexure_converter.py or equivalent document-type-specific converter. Do not reuse the EI annexure converter because EI converter extracts elemental impurities such as Pb, As, Cd, Hg, Co, V, Ni, etc., whereas residual solvent annexures require extracting solvent declarations and solvent limits. The RS converter must extract: supplier name, material name, material name candidates, document title, annexure type, solvent names, solvent limit values, units, raw text, page number, confidence, calculation basis, and evidence type. It must support numerical values such as NMT X ppm, X ppm, X%, BDL/ND if stated, and statements such as “solvents listed in USP <467> are not used”, “water is the only solvent used”, “no source for residual solvents”, “testing not required because solvent is not used or produced”, “ethyl alcohol may be present up to 0.5% maximum”, or “controlled by vendor specification”. The uploaded Dextrose annexure is a negative declaration stating USP <467>/ICH Q3C residual solvents are not used and water is the only solvent used; the uploaded Simethicone annexure is a no-source/no-testing-required style declaration; the uploaded Triethyl citrate annexure contains a specific ethanol statement where ethyl alcohol may be present up to 0.5%, which corresponds to 5000 ppm and drives the ethanol calculation. [1](https://drlglobal-my.sharepoint.com/personal/nitinreddyv_drreddys_com/_layouts/15/Doc.aspx?sourcedoc=%7B503FFB07-9F64-4F4F-93AA-512644B4254A%7D&file=Residual%20Solvent-%20Esomeprazole%20Mg%20DR%20OS%2009-02-2026%202.xlsx&action=default&mobileredirect=true)[2](https://drlglobal-my.sharepoint.com/personal/nitinreddyv_drreddys_com/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/Triethyl%20citrate%20%28%20Annexure%204%29.pdf)[3](https://drlglobal-my.sharepoint.com/personal/nitinreddyv_drreddys_com/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/Dextrose%20Anhydrous%20%28Annexure%2012%29.pdf)

The RS annexure converter must classify evidence type. Supported evidence types include: numerical solvent limit, percentage solvent limit, negative declaration/no solvent used, no-source/no-testing-required declaration, solvent used but controlled by specification, COA/specification statement, and ambiguous/missing solvent evidence. For numerical values, preserve raw value and raw unit, convert to ppm, and store converted_ppm. For percentage values, convert correctly: 0.5% = 5000 ppm. For NMT values, use the NMT value as the conservative calculation value. For negative declarations, do not invent numerical ppm values; mark solvent profile as no-use/not-applicable with evidence basis. For ambiguous text, do not silently assume zero; push the value to the verification screen. Every solvent value must carry source page, raw text, converted value, confidence, and calculation basis.

The RS converter must avoid the same failures observed in the EI annexure converter. It must never return a raw list as the top-level JSON; every converted annexure must return a consistent top-level dictionary/object schema, even if no solvent table or no numerical solvent values are found. The previous EI converter issue “list object has no attribute get” happened because one annexure returned a list instead of the expected object; this must not happen in RS. If the model returns a list, wrap it into the standard annexure object under a safe field such as extracted_items and mark schema_repaired = true. If extraction fails, return a structured error object rather than crashing the entire run. The report generator must also defensively validate every annexure object before calling .get(). No malformed annexure should crash the workflow.

The RS converter must also avoid the material-name extraction failures observed in EI. It must distinguish between generic document titles and actual material identity. Generic phrases such as “Product Quality Statement”, “Quality and Regulatory Information Summary”, “Product Regulatory Information”, “Safety Data Sheet”, “Material Characterization”, “Residual Solvents Statement”, and “Regulatory Information” are document types, not material names. The actual material name is usually the subject of the document, e.g., “Anhydrous Dextrose C”, “Dow Corning Q7-2243 LVA, Simethicone USP”, or “Triethyl Citrate NF/CAS# 77-93-0”. The converter must prioritize phrases after patterns such as “for: X”, “Product Name: X”, “Product identifier: X”, “Subject: X”, “RE: X”, “Product / Manufacturing plant: X”, “Supplier product number and name: X”, and composition tables where product identity is listed. It must not extract generic headings as material_name. It must preserve material_name_candidates for traceability.

Implement residual solvent annexure mapping separately from EI mapping. The mapping must link Excel components to RS annexures using product/material identity, supplier, filename, document title, material name candidates, and semantic equivalence. Do not rely only on exact string matching. The mapper must handle pharmacopeial suffixes, spelling variants, brand names, supplier product names, and shorthand such as Dextrose vs Glucose (Dextrose Anhydrous C), Simethicone vs Dow Corning Q7-2243 LVA Simethicone USP, Triethyl citrate vs TEC, etc. However, do not build product-specific hardcoded mappings. Use a general material identity resolver with normalized text, chemical synonym understanding, supplier/title/filename context, confidence scoring, and user confirmation for uncertain matches. Matched values must include matched_annexure, confidence, match_reason, evidence fields used, and whether user confirmation was required.

The RS workflow must support cases where Excel already contains solvent limits and daily exposures. In this mode, Excel is the primary calculation source, and annexures are supporting evidence/traceability. The system should extract the Excel solvent matrix, validate formulas and totals, map annexures for traceability, and render the report. It should not force recalculation from annexures if the Excel already contains approved-style calculation values. However, the system must still validate that Excel values are dimensionally consistent: Daily Exposure (mg) should approximately equal Amount in Maximum Dose (mg) × Limit (ppm) / 1,000,000. Total Daily Exposure per solvent must equal sum of component exposures. Residual solvent limit rows must be compared correctly. If Excel and annexure disagree, show warning and require user confirmation.

The RS workflow must also support basic Excel mode. If Excel only provides component names and component MDD/maximum daily intake, calculate exposures using solvent limits from annexures or user-confirmed values. If Excel provides only total product MDD but not component-level daily intake, the system must not allocate solvent risk blindly unless component composition is present and a safe derivation exists. If solvent limits are missing and annexures only say no solvents used, record negative declaration evidence. If solvent limits are missing and no negative declaration exists, block or request user input. The report must not silently treat missing solvent evidence as zero.

The verification screen is mandatory before generation. Show detected document type, product name, strength, dosage form, selected strength basis, no. of doses, maximum daily dose, total drug product intake, component list, quantity/unit, amount in maximum dose, solvent list, solvent limits in ppm, daily exposures in mg, total exposure per solvent, residual solvent USP <467>/ICH Q3C limits, calculation source for each value, annexure source, evidence type, confidence, assumptions, and warnings. Allow edits only to missing/low-confidence/inconsistent values. After confirmation, freeze the payload and generate the report.

The validation gate must be strict. Block or strongly prevent clean report generation if component amount in maximum dose cannot be determined, solvent value is missing or ambiguous for a quantitative component without a valid negative declaration, top-level annexure schema is malformed, material identity is missing or generic-only, Excel formulas are inconsistent beyond tolerance, total exposures do not reconcile with component exposures, unsupported unit conversion is required, solvent master data is missing for a listed solvent, or the report would conclude compliance while unresolved data gaps exist. False zeros must never be treated as real zeros. A zero is valid only if sourced from explicit Excel value, validated formula, negative declaration, no-source statement, or user-confirmed input.

Create a separate A4 renderer, e.g., generate_report_residual_solvent.js. It must render residual solvent-specific structure and nested solvent tables. Do not reuse EI generate_report.js class table builder. The RS calculation tables must have columns: Components, Quantity / unit (mg), Amount in Maximum Dose (mg), then grouped solvent headers where each solvent has Limit (ppm) and Daily Exposure (mg). Tables may be split across multiple solvent groups, for example Ethanol/Ethylene Glycol/1,4-Dioxane, then IPA/Tertiary butyl alcohol/Heptane, then Acetone/Methanol/Toluene. At the bottom, render Drug Product (mg), Total Daily Exposure, and Residual Solvent Limit as per current USP <467>. The renderer must handle nested headers cleanly, fit A4 width, avoid table overflow, avoid page borders if they create layout issues, avoid unnecessary asterisks or decorative symbols, and never hallucinate annexure names. Annexure names must come only from uploaded annexure metadata or user-confirmed values.

The RS report payload passed to renderer must be independent from EI payload. Use keys such as rs_meta, product_details, composition_table, supplier_declaration_table, solvent_matrix_tables, solvent_totals, solvent_limit_master, annexure_list, verification_audit, validation_warnings, conclusion_data, references, revision_history, signatures. Do not pass EI-specific keys like class1_2a, class2b, class3, ICH_PDE, 30pct_threshold, pde_route, or element_totals into RS renderer. Likewise, RS must not affect EI payload or renderer behavior.

The RS report narrative must be generated from structured data only. The LLM may draft objective, background, risk assessment summary, conclusion, and summary/conclusion, but it must not invent values, solvent limits, supplier declarations, annexure titles, or compliance statements. If any mandatory calculation or source evidence is unresolved, the conclusion must say assessment is incomplete or require user correction; it must not say compliant. If all solvent total exposures are below applicable limits and validation passes, the conclusion can state compliance with USP <467>/ICH Q3C Option 2 or the selected option. References should include USP <467> and ICH Q3C residual solvents guidance, but do not mix ICH Q3D EI references into the RS report.

The final implementation goal is a clean isolated Residual Solvent document type where app.py only routes orchestration, residual_solvent_excel_parser extracts either detailed or basic dose data, residual_solvent_annexure_converter extracts solvent declarations and limits safely, residual_solvent_mapper links components to annexures without product-specific hardcoding, residual_solvent_calculator computes exposure in mg/day, residual_solvent_validator prevents false compliance, and generate_report_residual_solvent.js renders the A4 nested-table report. Existing EI OSD/injection workflows, EI annexure converter, EI mapping, EI PDE constants, and EI renderer must remain untouched and unaffected.
##############
There are three critical remaining red flags in the EI annexure pipeline that must be understood and fixed without hardcoding product-specific/vendor-specific aliases or creating one-off mappings.

First, annexure mapping has improved but is still missing important edge cases. The system can now match many straightforward cases, but it still fails when the composition ingredient name and annexure material name represent the same material using different scientific, abbreviated, branded, or chemically equivalent wording. Examples include cases such as “Sodium CMC USP (Blanose 7LFPH)” not matching an annexure named “Blanose sodium carboxymethylcellulose”, and “Monobasic Na Phosphate Monohydrate USP” not matching “Monobasic sodium phosphate”. These are not missing annexures; the annexure JSONs exist, but the identity resolver fails because the current logic still depends too much on token overlap, pooled aliases, or deterministic matching. This will not scale to large document volumes because tomorrow there may be thousands of new material/vendor naming variations. The red flag is that the model is not sufficiently understanding semantic equivalence between abbreviation and full chemical name, e.g., CMC vs carboxymethylcellulose, Na vs sodium, branded/trade names vs chemical names, and hydrate/salt/grade descriptors. The mapping layer must not silently mark such valid annexures as “No match” when the annexure is present and scientifically corresponds to the ingredient.

Second, the annexure converter sometimes crashes with `Unexpected error: 'list' object has no attribute 'get'`. This means at least one annexure conversion output is being returned as a raw list instead of the expected structured dictionary/object. Downstream code assumes every annexure has dictionary-style fields such as `material_name`, `supplier_name`, `elements`, `filename`, etc., and therefore calls `.get()` on the annexure object. When the converter returns a list, usually because the model returned only an array of elements or an empty array instead of a full annexure JSON object, the pipeline crashes. This is a schema consistency issue between the converter and the report generator. Every converted annexure must always conform to the same top-level object schema, even when the annexure has no EI table, no detected elements, or only packaging/material characterization data. A malformed annexure should be flagged clearly, not allowed to crash the full run.

Third, annexure material name extraction is still inaccurate for non-standard annexures. In the Rubber Stopper / West Annexure 7 case, the actual document clearly states “Material Characterization for Elastomeric Formulation 4432/50 Gray”, but the converter extracted the material name as “Material Characterization” and candidates such as “Material Characterization - Insights from the Experts”. This is wrong because “Material Characterization” is only the document type/title, while “Elastomeric Formulation 4432/50 Gray” is the actual material identity. The converter is currently biased toward prominent document titles and page headings rather than identifying the subject/material being characterized. This issue is especially visible in material characterization, extractables/leachables, container closure, vial, stopper, tubing, and filter annexures, where the true material name may appear in a phrase like “Material Characterization for X”, “Extractables Study for X”, “Validation Guide for X”, or “Assessment of X”. The converter must distinguish generic document descriptors from the actual subject of the document. If the converter extracts a generic title instead of the material identity, downstream mapping and annexure traceability become unreliable.

These three failures together cause serious downstream scientific risk: valid annexures may be present but marked as unmatched; malformed annexure outputs may crash the system; and incorrectly extracted material names may pollute the annexure list and mapping pool. When mapping fails, concentration values default to zero, exposure values become zero, and the report may incorrectly appear compliant even though annexure data was not properly linked. The system must not treat false zeros as real values and must not generate a clean compliance conclusion when quantitative ingredients remain unmatched or annexure identity extraction is unreliable. The core issue is not the EI calculation formula or PDE rows; the issue is annexure identity extraction, schema consistency, and semantic material matching.
